Based on the graphic above, the temperature might be below average during the last part of January through early February, but it might be that the temp might be a few degrees colder, but still around 40°.  Or it it might be several degrees lower, which could put the temp below freezing.  Also, to be helpful, the weather forecast needs to include more information than just the temperature. I watch the weather forecast EVERY NIGHT at 10 pm. My decisions about what I will do the next day are determined by these forecasts. The channel I watch usually includes the 14 to 90-day outlook you are curious about (however the Federal Govt map you showed actually shows an accurate legend unlike my local station). Any time the forecast is more than 2 to 4 days, it starts to be very inaccurate. My personal belief is we don't have a large enough base of data to accurately predict weather temperature and precipitation for 4 days out much less 14 to 90. Our data from the satellite era (about 50 years worth) is good, data before then is less helpful. And more the 150 years ago data pretty much doesn't exist. 150 years of depth with only 50 years being accurate enough to be useful is just not enough data to build a system on. 


NOW let's get into what would ACTUALLY happen. In 2020, we sent many good people home. Many of them did not return to work. People hired to replace these experienced weathermen are not just inexperienced, they are likely to have been hired because they are a minority group of some sort, NOT because they actually showed the ability to do the calculations required to predict weather. Meteorology is not an easy science to learn and I doubt the Federal Government did their due diligence to hire the best and brightest meteorologists to replace the people who retired during Covid. If the State of Oklahoma were hiring the people for this project, I am much more likely to trust they chose based on skills and ability to understand and learn about weather.

It also seems we no longer have seasons. It goes from cold weather one day to scorching hot the next. Sometimes that happens from morning to night. It seems as though a forecast is just a suggestion rather than what actually happens. The accuracy of forecast seems to be a thing from the past. It seems as though you'd have to have a play by play of the forecast for the entire day, hour by hour. Even then it changes drastically. Also living in the country by the lake, we never have a forecast. It's always only for the major cities from us. There's no doubt the weather has shifted drastically from what I remember when I was young. Tornadoes seem to have a different trajectory than before. There's a major shift in these paths. It just changes too rapidly these days. It's like they can't keep up. My father-in-law says he remembers when they predicted weather so accurately they could tell you which side of town the rain would stop at, down to which side of the street. It seems as though with advancing technology, forecast are worse not better. I'm not sure it's worth the tax payers time or money.
I would be curious to see what else the proposal would affect, other than raising taxes.
